snippet.textDisplay: It's a good scene, probably the best thing Chibnall's written so far, but I have a problem with it. The Master says "A man very close to my heart"... except The Master has two hearts. And come to think of it, has it ever been established in the Chibnall era that Time Lords have two hearts, or even that The Doctor is actually a Time Lord and not just a quirky human from the future? And how come The Doctor didn't recognize The Master? I thought Time Lords could always recognize eachother regardless of regeneration, as established in the first appearance of the Time Lords way back in "The War Games". This is the biggest problem I have with the Chibnall era, it just feels disconnected from the rest of the series because it contradicts previously established rules.

snippet.textDisplay: Is it me or is Jodie Whittaker's Doctor the most clueless and stupid. She's got a decent performance but her character asks too many questions rather than figuring them out herself like pretty much every other Doctor. She has also never had a moment where she utterly wipes the floor of her enemies with pure intelligence and wit. Most of the Doctors have had several of these moments in each season and she's basically just running around fixing things passively or with a swish and flick of her sonic screwdriver. It doesn't make for good characterisation and so far she comes off as the most bland Doctor yet. I wish the writers would give her a better chance because she has much more potential.

snippet.textDisplay:
Everyone’s been thinking that O comes between Saxon and Missy, but I think I’ve cracked the code of how he could actually come after Missy despite her redemption! It ties into the theory of how the circumstances of each of the Doctor’s regenerations influence his next incarnation. For example, the First Doctor being surrounded by younger, goofier people made him want to take on those traits himself during his regeneration into the Second Doctor, the Second Doctor being mad about his forced regeneration made him more prickly as the Third (at first), the Ninth Doctor warming up to Rose made Ten become more “human” in personality and fall in love with her, Eleven mellowing out over a very long period of time made him want to become old and grandfatherly again as Twelve, etc.

You can even see this in the Master’s regenerations. Ainley heavily mimicked Delgado because he had spent so much time trying to not lose his essence as the decaying Masters, making him want to revert back to what he was, Jacobi died being envious of Ten’s youth and energy, making John Simm exactly that, Simm died respecting Missy for outwitting him (anger about her joining the Doctor aside), and after a lifetime or two of being misogynistic (seen in his behavior to Chantho and Lucy Saxon), could finally accept the potential strength of women and became one.

So Missy becoming O after her redemption? Well we see the recurring trait of the Master, at his/her core, valuing power above all else (Delgado Master: “The point is that one must rule or serve- it’s a basic law of life!”) Getting killed by her own past self probably gave her a realization in her dying moments that her softening up to the Doctor made her weak, weak enough to get killed by her own past self. So she wanted to be more like who she was, hence O’s return to cartoony evil and Simm-inspired mannerisms. I could be wrong of course, but it does make sense.

Surviving the actual blast? That’s easier to explain. If Ainley could literally get burned to ashes and come back with only the explanation “Come, come, the whole universe knows I’m indestructible!”, later survivals not withstanding, then this one really isn’t any different.
